05049nam a22006375i 9780804794497DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047944977 a10.1515/97808047944972doi  a(DE-B1597)563714  a(OCoLC)1178769371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV600 2010b.U57 2015eb 7aBUS0710002bisacsh04a363.34/95809832231 aUseem, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeadership Dispatches :bChile's Extraordinary Comeback from Disaster /cMichael Useem, Howard Kunreuther, Erwann Michel-Kerjan. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHigh Reliability and Crisis Management00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue: A Quiet Summer Evening -- t1. Twelve Days before Entering the Presidential Office -- t2. One of the Most Intense Events Ever Recorded -- t3. First Order of Business -- t4. Frameworks for Action -- t5. Presidential Leadership -- t6. Tiered Leadership -- t7. Financing Recovery -- t8. Insurance Payouts for Recovery -- t9. Private Giving for Recovery -- t10. Execution and Expectations -- t11. Vulnerability and Readiness -- t12. Civil Action -- t13. Long-term Disaster Recovery -- t14. Rescuing Thirty-three Miners -- t15. Leadership Dispatches -- tEpilogue: A Quiet Summer Afternoon -- tList of Tables, Figures, and Photogaphs -- tNote -- tReferences -- tIndividuals Interviewed -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn February 27, 2010, Chile was rocked by a violent earthquake five hundred times more powerful than the one that hit Haiti just six weeks prior. The Chilean earthquake devastated schools, hospitals, roads, and homes, paralyzing the country for weeks and causing economic damage that was equal to 18 percent of Chile's GDP. This calamity hit just as an incumbent political regime was packing its bags and a new administration was preparing to take office. For most countries, it would have taken years, if not decades, to recover from such an event. Yet, only one year later, Chile's economy had reached a six percent annual growth rate. In Leadership Dispatches, Michael Useem, Howard Kunreuther, and Erwann Michel-Kerjan look at how the nation's leaders-in government, business, religion, academia, and beyond-facilitated Chile's recovery. They attribute Chile's remarkable comeback to a two-part formula consisting of strong national leadership on the one hand, and deeply rooted institutional practices on the other. Coupled with strategic, deliberative thinking, these levers enabled Chile to bounce back quickly and exceed its prior national performance. The authors make the case that the Chilean story contains lessons for a broad range of organizations and governments the world over. Large-scale catastrophes of many kinds-from technological meltdowns to disease pandemics-have been on the rise in recent years. Now is the time to seek ideas and guidance from other leaders who have triumphed in the wake of a disaster. In this vein, Leadership Dispatches is both a remarkable story of resilience and an instructive look at how those with the greatest responsibility for a country, company, or community should lead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChile Earthquake, Chile, 2010 (February 27) 0aEarthquake reliefzChile. 0aEmergency managementzChile. 0aLeadershipzChile. 4aDisasters. 4acatastrophes. 4aearthquakes. 4aleadership. 4aresilience. 4arisk. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Leadership.2bisacsh1 aKunreuther, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMiche